[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-gubernatorial-election] The **1849 California gubernatorial election** was held on November 13, 1849, to elect the first governor of California.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-gubernatorial-election] Peter Hardeman Burnett won in a five-way race.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-gubernatorial-election] Burnett was subsequently sworn in as governor on December 20, 1849, with the military governor, Bennet C.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-gubernatorial-election] Riley, ceding *de facto* executive authority to him.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-gubernatorial-election] However, California did not officially become a state until September 9, 1850, as part of the Compromise of 1850.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-gubernatorial-election] Peter Hardeman Burnett had only arrived in California a year prior to the election of 1849, but was known for his work in Oregon Territory as a judge in their territory's Supreme Court.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-gubernatorial-election] On January 6, 1849, in a meeting of prominent men in Sacramento, he was appointed President of a committee that formally requested a provisional government to be established in California.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-gubernatorial-election] This committee would work with Bennet C.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-gubernatorial-election] Riley, the final military governor of California, to establish election procedures, and delegate counts.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The **1849 California lieutenant gubernatorial election** was held on November 13, 1849, in order to elect the first Lieutenant Governor of California upon California acquiring statehood on September 9, 1850.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Candidate John McDougal defeated candidate Richard Roman, candidate John B.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Winn, candidate and former Supreme Judge of the Provisional Government of Oregon Peter Hardeman Burnett and candidate Pablo de la Guerra.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] On election day, November 13, 1849, candidate John McDougal won the election by a margin of 5,258 votes against his foremost opponent candidate Richard Roman.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] McDougal was sworn in as the 1st Lieutenant Governor of California on December 20, 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] States held the **1848–49 United States House of Representatives elections** between August 7, 1848, and November 11, 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Each state set a date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 31st United States Congress convened on December 3, 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] The new U.S. state of Wisconsin elected its first Representatives.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Anticipating statehood, as ratified in September 1850, California held Federal elections beforehand, increasing the size of the House to 233 seats.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] These elections spanned the 1848 United States presidential election and took place immediately after the U.S. victory over Mexico in the Mexican–American War.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] The Whigs lost their House majority as Democrats, whose support had driven the war, won a plurality.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Among minor parties, the new Free Soil Party, which opposed slavery in the Western territories, won nine Northern seats, while the American or Know Nothing Party retained one.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Despite winning most of their seats at Whig expense, the Free Soil Party had coalesced in 1848 largely as a result of a Democratic Party split in New York, the most populous state.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] The new party thus drove an unusual Whig sweep in New York elections, temporarily masking Whig decline.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] After a gold discovery in January 1848, California boomed, drawing rapid migration of new residents and creating immediate pressure for statehood.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] The Compromise of 1850, though largely crafted in the Senate, was also passed by the House, brokering its admission to the Union.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] As no party held a majority when Congress convened, the election of a Speaker proved contentious.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] The Whigs were sectionally split, with Northern Whigs nominating incumbent speaker Robert C.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Winthrop of Massachusetts and Southern Whigs supporting Meredith P.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Democrats primarily supported Howell Cobb of Georgia; 13 other Democratic hopefuls also garnered support.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] The small Free Soil Party supported David Wilmot of Pennsylvania, author of the Wilmot Proviso, calling attention to slave power's hold over both major parties.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] After nearly three weeks of heated debate, the House suspended its majority rule for the Speaker election, enabling Cobb to be elected on the 63rd ballot by plurality.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] An additional seat was apportioned to Wisconsin.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Two seats were allocated to California upon its admission on September 9, 1850, increasing the size of the House to 233 seats.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Elections were held August 6, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] In California two at-large members were elected November 13, 1849 in anticipation of statehood and seated September 11, 1850.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Elections were held April 2, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Florida's single at-large member was elected October 2, 1848.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Elections were held August 10, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Elections were held November 5, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Elections were held October 3, 1849 elections were after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the new term, but still before the Congress convened in December 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Elections were held November 5–6, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Elections were held March 13, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p01] Elections were held August 7, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p02] Elections were held April 4, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p02] Elections were held April 26, 1849, after the March 4, 1849 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p02] Wisconsin members were first elected in advance of its June 1848 statehood.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p02] It elected two members to finish the current term in the 30th Congress, and then it gained an elected an additional member for elections to the 31st Congress.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p02] Wisconsin's two members were elected May 8, 1848.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p02] Wisconsin's three members were elected November 7, 1848.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p02] Going into these elections, there were no incumbent delegates, because the only territory — Wisconsin Territory — became a state in 1848.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california-p02] Two new territories — Minnesota Territory and Oregon Territory — were granted delegates in 1849.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] The **1849 United States Senate elections in California** were held on December 20, 1849, by the California State Legislature to elect two U.S.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Senators (Class 1 and Class 3) to represent the State of California in the United States Senate.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1849-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Gwin were elected over several other challengers.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] The **1850–51 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1850 and 1851, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 1.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] The Democratic Party lost seats, but retained a majority in the Senate.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] This was the last election until 2006 that the Class 1 Vermont seat voted for a non-Republican.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] In these elections, the winners were seated during 1850 or in 1851 before March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] In these regular elections, the winners were elected for the term beginning March 4, 1851; ordered by state.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] All of the elections involved the Class 1 seats.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] In late these elections, the winners were elected in 1851 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] In this regular election, the winner was elected for the term beginning March 4, 1853.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Underwood retired and the Know Nothing Lieutenant Governor of Kentucky John Burton Thompson was elected early, December 13, 1851, far in advance of the 1853 term, as was common practice at the time.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Long-term Whig and former-United States Secretary of State Henry Clay announced his resignation December 17, 1851 from the class 3 seat, to be effective September 6, 1852.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Whig Archibald Dixon was elected December 30, 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Before Clay's resignation was effective, he died June 24, 1852.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Democratic Secretary of State of Kentucky David Meriwether was appointed July 6, 1852 pending the effective date of the special election.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Dixon was then seated September 1, 1852 to finish the term that would end in 1855.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Reverdy Johnson won election in 1844 but retired to become the United States Attorney General.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] In order to fill his seat, David Stewart was elected as a temporary appointment until a successor could be elected.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Thomas Pratt won election by an unknown margin of votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Thomas Pratt won election to a full term by an unknown margin of votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] In 1851, Democrats gained control of the legislature in coalition with the Free Soilers.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] However, the legislature deadlocked on this Senate race, as Democrats refused to vote for Charles Sumner (the Free Soilers' choice).
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] The election in New York was held on February 4 and March 18 and 19, 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Dickinson (Democratic) had been elected in 1845 to this seat, and his term would expire on March 3, 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] The opposing factions of the Democratic Party in New York, the "Barnburners" and the "Hunkers", had reunited at the State election in November 1850, and managed to have almost their whole State ticket elected, only Horatio Seymour was defeated for Governor by a plurality of 262 votes.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] At the State election in November 1849, 14 Seward Whigs, 3 Silver Gray Whigs and 15 Democrats were elected for a two-year term (1850–1851) in the State Senate.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] At the State election in November 1850, a Whig majority was elected to the Assembly for the session of 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] The 74th New York State Legislature met from January 7 to April 17, and from June 10 to July 11, 1851, at Albany, New York.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Ex-Governor of New York Hamilton Fish was the candidate of the Whig Party, but was also a close friend of Henry Clay who was one of the leaders of the Fillmore faction in Washington, D.C.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] He was thus considered the only viable compromise candidate.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] The Silver Grays asked Fish to pledge his support for the Compromise, but Fish refused to make any comment, saying that he did not seek the office, and that the legislators should vote guided by Fish's known political history.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Fish had earlier stated his opposition against the Fugitive Slave Law of 1850 but was believed to support most of the remainder of the Compromise.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Nevertheless, Silver Gray State Senator James W.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Beekman declared that he would not vote for Fish for personal reasons, a dislike stemming from the time when they were fellow students at Columbia University.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] The State Legislature met on February 4, the legally prescribed day, to elect a U.S.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] In the Assembly, Fish received a majority of 78 to 49.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] In the State Senate the vote stood 16 for Fish and 16 votes for a variety of candidates, among them Beekman's vote for Francis Granger.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] After a second ballot with the same result, Beekman moved to adjourn, which was carried by the casting vote of the lieutenant governor, and no nomination was made.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Guinnip offered a resolution to declare John Adams Dix elected to the U.S.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Babcock, the resolution was laid on the table, i.e. consideration was postponed.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] On February 15, Guinnip again offered a resolution to declare John Adams Dix elected to the U.S.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Johnson offered an amendment to this resolution, declaring Daniel S.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] On motion of Senator Marius Schoonmaker, the resolution was laid on the table too.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] On March 18, when two Democratic State Senators were absent, having gone to New York City, the Whigs persuaded the Democrats in a 14-hour session to re-open the U.S.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Senate election, and Senate electionin the small hours of March 19 Fish was nominated by a vote of 16 to 12 (Beekman, Johnson (both Whigs), Thomas B.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Fish was the choice of both the Assembly and the Senate, and was declared elected.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Incumbent Senator Thomas Corwin (Whig) resigned July 20, 1850 to become U.S.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Thomas Ewing (Whig) was appointed July 20, 1850 to finish the term.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Benjamin Wade (Whig) was elected late on March 15, 1851, on the 37th ballot over Ewing.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] The Pennsylvania election was held January 14, 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1850-united-states-senate-elections-in-california] Richard Brodhead was elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly to the United States Senate.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The **1851 California lieutenant gubernatorial election** was held on September 3, 1851, in order to elect the lieutenant governor of California.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Democratic nominee and former Mayor of Stockton Samuel Purdy defeated Whig nominee Drury P.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] On election day, September 3, 1851, Democratic nominee Samuel Purdy won the election by a margin of 3,717 votes against his opponent Whig nominee Drury P.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Baldwin, thereby retaining Democratic control over the office of lieutenant governor.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Purdy was sworn in as the 3rd lieutenant governor of California on January 8, 1852.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] States held the **1850–51 United States House of Representatives elections** between August 5, 1850, and November 4, 1851, during President Millard Fillmore's term.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Each state set a date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 32nd United States Congress convened on December 1, 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Thirty-one states held elections, for 233 House seats.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] After previously winning a plurality, the Democrats won a majority over the rival Whigs.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Incumbent Whig President Millard Fillmore, who had succeeded to the Presidency in July 1850 after the death of more charismatic General Zachary Taylor, lacked a strong political base.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] The Compromise of 1850, which admitted California alone as a free state in exchange for concessions to slave state interests, began integration of the Mexican Cession.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] It appeared in the short term that Congress had politically feasible options to contain sectionalism and to reduce tensions over expanding slavery in the Western United States.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] This optimism soon would prove unfounded.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] In the South, two short-lived minor parties formed, one supporting, and the other opposing, the Compromise of 1850.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] The supporting Union Party won 10 seats, while the opposing Southern Rights Party won three.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] The Free Soil Party, which opposed the expansion of slavery into the Western territories, lost seats and was reduced to four Representatives.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] One district in Massachusetts had been vacant in the 31st Congress.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] The previous election had 1 Know-Nothing and 1 Independent.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Elections were held August 4, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] The election was held August 4, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] California's members were elected late, at-large statewide, September 3, 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] There were nevertheless seated with the rest of the House at the beginning of the first session.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Elections were held April 7, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] The election was held November 12, 1850.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Elections were held November 4, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Elections were held October 1, 1851 elections were after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the new term, but still before the Congress convened in December 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Elections were held November 11, 1850, but at least one district's elections went to multiple ballots into 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Elections were held November 3–4, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Elections were held March 11, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Elections were held August 7, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Elections were held April 2, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Elections were held October 14–15, 1850.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1851-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-california] Elections were held October 23, 1851, after the March 4, 1851 beginning of the term, but before the House first convened in December 1851.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The **1871 California lieutenant gubernatorial election** was held on September 6, 1871, in order to elect the lieutenant governor of California.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Republican nominee and incumbent California State Treasurer Romualdo Pacheco defeated Democratic nominee and incumbent President pro tempore of the California State Senate Edward J.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] On election day, September 6, 1871, Republican nominee Romualdo Pacheco won the election by a margin of 5,158 votes against his opponent Democratic nominee Edward J.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Lewis, thereby gaining Republican control over the office of lieutenant governor.
[src:1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election/1871-california-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Pacheco was sworn in as the 12th lieutenant governor of California on December 8, 1871.
